<p><rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1925">Bernhard van Meurs</rs>, <ref target="biblio.xml#lit_600">‘De koning op het torenplat’</ref>. Van Meurs 1877, pp. 141-142. Translated from <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_841">Ludwig Uhland</rs>. The source text has ‘ook’ instead of ‘steeds’ (l. 160).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="8" xml:id="note-t-8">
                            

<p><rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1925">Bernhard van Meurs</rs>, <ref target="biblio.xml#lit_601">‘Een wintermorgen’</ref>. Van Meurs 1877, pp. 151-152. Translated from <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_841">Ludwig Uhland</rs>.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="9" xml:id="note-t-9">
                            

<p><rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1925">Bernhard van Meurs</rs>, <ref target="biblio.xml#lit_602">‘De leeuweriken’</ref>. Van Meurs 1877, p. 157. Translated from <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_841">Ludwig Uhland</rs>. The last two lines in the source text read ‘Eén belust op tierelier / Fladdert in mijn binnenst’ hier!’ (l. 193-194).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="10" xml:id="note-t-10">
                            

<p><rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1925">Bernhard van Meurs</rs>, <ref target="biblio.xml#lit_603">‘Het kerkhof in de lente’</ref>. Van Meurs 1877, p. 153. Translated from <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_841">Ludwig Uhland</rs>. Van Gogh quotes the first and third stanzas but omits the three lines of the second stanza, probably because of their harsh tone: ‘Ach, ik vrees dat straks de dood / Naar uw vunzen donkren schoot / Een der mijnen weg zal dragen’ (Oh, I fear that death / Will soon take one of mine / To your dark and filthy lap).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
